yond the reach of democratic politics, but this appearance—like so much about money—is deceptive. Even when the politics of money is impossible to ignore, its proper democratic role can be difficult to discern. Stefan Eich examines six crucial episodes of monetary crisis, recovering the neglected political theories of money in the thought of such figures as Aristotle, John Locke, Johann Gottlieb Fichte, Karl Marx, and John Maynard Keynes. He shows how these layers of crisis have come to define the way we look at money, and argues that informed public debate about money requires a better appreciation of the diverse political struggles over its meaning.Recovering foundational ideas at the intersection of monetary rule and democratic politics, The Currency of Politics explains why only through greater awareness of the historical limits of monetary politics can we begin to articulate more democratic conceptions of money.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMonetary policyxHistory. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aMoney, economic justice, depoliticization, monetary sovereignty, monetary policy, central banks, inflation, Aristotle, Locke, Fichte, Marx, Keynes, Hayek, Habermas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074973140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691235448?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691235448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691235448/original  a978-3-11-074973-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK